english:
  title: A Preface Presented to the Venerable Huanweng
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |
    A monk named Tanru came to my gate and made this request: "I follow the Caodong school, and this year of Dingsi marks a great selection. My lay surname is Zheng of Yingri. The abbot of Yanfu Temple, Great Master Zhu'an Zhenong, is my teacher. I have lived twenty-seven years, yet lack a monastic name, and my peers find it difficult to address me. My teacher named me Huanweng, drawn from the chapter on Samantabhadra in the Avatamsaka Sutra. When I asked him to explain, the master said: 'Tanru, what does your name mean? Tan means open and smooth—without fixed anchor in the center, nothing to lean upon without, dwelling in ease and gaining naturally. This must be the realm of that which neither wavers nor moves. And yet, observe the world: is it not illusion?' 'Yes, illusion.' 'Body and mind: are they not illusion?' 'Yes, illusion.' 'The buddhas of three ages, the patriarchs of all lineages: are they not illusion?' 'Yes, illusion.' 'My words and your hearing: is this not illusion?' 'Yes, illusion.' The master said, 'I have heard that Hanshan the Shepherd, though concealed, speaks now in the language of illusion. Go seek him out, and he will not refuse you.' So I venture to make this request."

    I replied: "The teacher's own master—he is of the old scholarly line, nourished his body on fine grains and silken robes, cultivated his nature through poetry, books, rites and music, yet stood apart in solitary transcendence, caring nothing for the world. Truly, he has grasped the essence of both 'as-is' and 'illusion.' Though I myself have not studied such things, let me inquire further of the Venerable One."

    The Venerable said: "The world today is the realm of material form. All sentient beings are the realm of emotion. All buddhas are the realm of perfect wisdom and awakening. These three interpenetrate without obstruction. Thus the wisdom of 'as-is' perpetually shines alone. We call this the world. All dwell in illusion. Without 'as-is,' we cannot seek illusion. Without illusion, we cannot seek 'as-is.' So how could principle and phenomenon ever compete with one another?"

    I said: "Truly, you are a vessel of perfect functioning. Observing your words, I see one meaning: 'as-is' is itself illusion. Another meaning: 'as-is' shall become illusion. When we first view through illusion, there is object and subject—this is duality. When finally 'as-is' becomes illusion, there is neither object nor subject—this is non-duality. When both thing and self are forgotten, mind and trace are not two. This is the utmost. Another day, when Huanweng sits in stillness and right mindfulness, should he gain understanding of this teaching, let him tell me whether today's words are true or false. I shall listen with an open heart."

    Tanru then asked: "Our teacher says you speak in the language of illusion to the people. Can you let us hear how speech itself becomes illusion?"

    I answered: "When sound emerges, it requires throat, tongue, lips, and teeth working together—only then does sound arise. When it is inscribed in writing, it requires brush, ink, paper, inkstone, and water working together—only then does form take shape. And in the realm of turning characters, borrowed sounds, phonetic forms, and meaning between—the transformations are so manifold that even assigning names takes endless turns. Yet if we analyze it carefully, where truly does sound reside? From where does writing derive? Is this not illusion itself?"

    Tanru bowed deeply and said: "Our teacher truly understands you. What he meant by asking 'is this not illusion?' surely you understand. I wish to become your student."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Caodong (Caogxi) refers to one of the major schools of Chan Buddhism, tracing its lineage to Patriarch Huineng of Caoxi.
  - key: ''
    value: The Avatamsaka Sutra (Huayan Jing), specifically the chapter on the bodhisattva Samantabhadra, is a foundational text in East Asian Buddhism discussing the nature of reality and illusion.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three ages' refer to the past, present, and future buddhas in Buddhist cosmology.
  - key: ''
    value: Hanshan the Shepherd (Hanshan Muyin) was a literatus-monk known for his wit and philosophical discourse.
  - key: ''
    value: The concepts of 'as-is' (如, ru) and illusion (幻, huan) represent fundamental Buddhist philosophical categories—the unchanging nature of reality and the illusory nature of phenomenal manifestation.
  - key: ''
    value: The fourfold etymology mentioned—turning characters (转注), borrowed sounds (假借), phonetic composition (形声), and semantic association (事意)—are traditional Chinese methods of understanding how written language functions and derives meaning.
